Dose responsive effects of subcutaneous pentosan polysulfate injection in mucopolysaccharidosis type VI rats and comparison to oral treatment.
Increasing concentrations of dermatan sulfate (DS) reduce the viability of the cells in both ARSB deficiency and controls, but hardly influence apoptosis.

Four pediatric patients with diseases potentially curable by bone marrow transplantation (BMT)--i.e., common variable immune deficiency, Wiskott-Aldrich Syndrome (WAS), mucopolysaccharidosis type VI, and mucopolysaccharidosis type I received a conditioning regimen consisting of busulfan and cyclophosphamide prior to BMT from HLA-identical, mixed leukocyte culture (MLC)-unreactive siblings.
